Question 1

Create a graph that shows the distribution of companies in the dataset by State (ie how many are in each state). There are a lot of States, so consider which axis you should use. This visualization is ultimately going to be consumed on a ‘portrait’ oriented screen (ie taller than wide), which should further guide your layout choices.

We’ll first grab states with the highest volume of companies, and group the rest into a column called ‘Other’.

# Answer Question 1 here
inc_state_summary <- inc %>%
                      group_by(State) %>%
                      summarise(
                        number = n_distinct(Name),
                      ) %>%
                      arrange(desc(number))

inc_state_summary <- rbind(inc_state_summary[c(1:24),],
                           (inc_state_summary[c(25:nrow(inc_state_summary)),] %>% 
                            summarise(
                            State = 'Other',
                            number = sum(number))))

Horizontal Bar Chart

Let’s plot the results. Note that we are making some adjustments to ensure the order is preserved. Also, we want to show ‘Other’ at the end, even if it has a high count. Let’s also get rid of the legend, since it’ll add no value here.
inc_state_summary$State <- factor(inc_state_summary$State, levels = rev(inc_state_summary$State))

ggplot(inc_state_summary ,  
       aes(State, 
           number)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity",
            aes(fill=State)) +
  coord_flip() + 
  ggtitle("Number of Firms by State") +
  ylab("Number of Firms") + 
  xlab("State") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Quesiton 2

Lets dig in on the state with the 3rd most companies in the data set. Imagine you work for the state and are interested in how many people are employed by companies in different industries. Create a plot that shows the average and/or median employment by industry for companies in this state (only use cases with full data, use R’s complete.cases() function.) In addition to this, your graph should show how variable the ranges are, and you should deal with outliers.

We’ll filter for New York State (the state with the 3rd most companies in the dataset). Let’s once again grab the industries with the highest employee count, and group the rest into an ‘Other’ column. We’ll grab the median and standard deviation for employees in companies by industry. Note that we’ll have to filter out industries with fewer than two companies, since we can’t get aggregate metrics for those.
# Answer Question 2 here

# pre group dataframe
inc_pre_group <- inc[complete.cases(inc),] %>%
                      filter(State=='NY')

top_industries <- (inc_pre_group %>% 
                      group_by(Industry) %>%
                      summarise(
                        total_emp = sum(Employees),
                      ) %>%
                      arrange(desc(total_emp)))$Industry[1:10]

inc_pre_group$Industry <- as.character(inc_pre_group$Industry)

inc_pre_group$Industry[!inc_pre_group$Industry %in% top_industries] <- 'Other'

# grouped dataframe
inc_ny <- inc_pre_group %>%
            group_by(Industry) %>%
            summarise(
              number = n_distinct(Name),
              Med_emp = median(Employees, na.rm = TRUE),
              Std_emp = var(Employees, na.rm = TRUE)^(.5)
            ) %>%
            filter(number > 1) %>%
            arrange(desc(Med_emp))

# Make sure 'Other' factor is shown last
inc_ny <- rbind(inc_ny[!inc_ny$Industry == 'Other',],
                inc_ny[inc_ny$Industry == 'Other',])

Bubble Plot

Let’s first plot the results in a bubble plot.
# Preserve order of factors
inc_ny$Industry <- factor(inc_ny$Industry, levels = inc_ny$Industry)

bubble_ny <- ggplot(inc_ny, aes(Med_emp, 
                        Std_emp, 
                        size = number,
                        color = Industry))
bubble_ny + 
geom_point() +
theme(legend.key=element_blank(), legend.key.size=unit(.3,"point")) +
guides(colour=guide_legend(nrow=20)) +
ggtitle("Employees Count within Firms by Industry in NY") +
ylab("Standard Deviation of Employee Count") + 
xlab("Median Number of Employees") +
scale_size(range = c(.1, 12))

Box and Whisker Plot

We can see that Business Products and Services clearly has a lot of variance in its portfolio of companies. Next, let’s visualize the distribution of head-count by industry using a box and whisker plot.
# Preserve order of factors
inc_pre_group$Industry <- factor(inc_pre_group$Industry, levels = inc_ny$Industry)

inc_box_plot <- ggplot(inc_pre_group, 
                       aes(Industry, 
                           Employees,
                           color = Industry))
inc_box_plot + 
geom_boxplot() + 
theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1),
     legend.key=element_blank(), 
     legend.key.size=unit(.4,"point")) +
ggtitle("Employees Count within Firms by Industry in NY") +
ylab("Employee Count") + 
xlab("Industry")

Dealing with Outliers

We can see that the outliers are not allowing us to analyze the important information closely. Fortunately, since the plots show the median and quartiles, the plots are robust to outliers. Let’s zoom in and try again.
inc_box_plot + 
geom_boxplot() + 
theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1),
     legend.key=element_blank(), 
     legend.key.size=unit(.4,"point")) +
ggtitle("Employees Count within Firms by Industry in NY") +
ylab("Employee Count") + 
xlab("Industry") +
coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 710))

Question 3

Now imagine you work for an investor and want to see which industries generate the most revenue per employee. Create a chart that makes this information clear. Once again, the distribution per industry should be shown.

Since we want to preserve the distributions, we cannot group our data. However, we can create a temporary grouping to get industries with the highest median revenue per employee. We’ll lump the rest into a category called ‘Other’ again.
# Only complete cases
inc_rev <- inc[complete.cases(inc),]

# Temporary grouping to get top industries
top_industries <- (inc_rev %>%
            group_by(Industry) %>%
            summarise(Med_rev_emp = median(Revenue/Employees)) %>% 
                      arrange(desc(Med_rev_emp)) %>% 
                      select(Industry))$Industry[1:10]

inc_rev$Industry <- as.character(inc_rev$Industry)

inc_rev$Industry[!inc_rev$Industry %in% top_industries] <- 'Other'

# Create column for revenue per employee
inc_rev <- inc_rev %>% 
            mutate(Rev_emp = Revenue/Employees)

Box and Whisker Plot

inc_rev$Industry <- factor(inc_rev$Industry, levels = c(as.character(top_industries),'Other'))

rev_box_plot <- ggplot(inc_rev, 
                       aes(Industry, 
                           Rev_emp,
                           color = Industry))
rev_box_plot + 
geom_boxplot() + 
theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1),
     legend.key=element_blank(), 
     legend.key.size=unit(.4,"point")) +
ggtitle(" Distribution Revenue per Employee \n for Firms by Industry") +
ylab("Revenue per Employee") + 
xlab("Industry")

Let’s get back to bubble charts and visualize indistry, median revenue per employee, median employee count as well as median revenue. We’ll first need to create our dataframe.
# grouped dataframe
inc_rev_group <- inc_rev %>%
                  group_by(Industry) %>%

                    Number = n_distinct(Name),
